    <li><strong>Vyazovskiy et al. (Nature, 2011):</strong> Demonstrated "local sleep" in individual cortical neurons during wakefulness in sleep-deprived rodents — establishing the neurophysiological precedent for the 2026 ADHD finding</li>
    <li><strong>Monastra et al. (Neuropsychology, 1999):</strong> Sample of 482 children and adolescents; elevated theta/beta EEG ratios distinguished ADHD subjects from controls — an early signal of sleep-associated oscillatory differences</li>
    <li><strong>Cortese et al. (Sleep Medicine Reviews):</strong> Extensive documentation of ADHD-sleep comorbidity, noting sleep problems appear in unmedicated ADHD patients at rates far exceeding general population baselines</li>
    <li><strong>Zentall & Zentall (1983):</strong> Early arousal-deficit hypothesis of ADHD — proposed hyperactivity as compensatory response to chronically low cortical arousal; precursor to the current wakefulness-regulation framing</li>
    <li><strong>Primary 2026 study:</strong> "Sleep-Like Neural Activity During Wakefulness in ADHD" — identified sleep-associated delta/theta oscillations intruding into waking cortical activity in ADHD brains (ScienceDaily, March 17, 2026; primary journal pending confirmation)</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="diagnostic-implications" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Question the Field Now Has to Answer</h2>
  <p>The therapeutic implications of this finding are real, but they are not yet actionable, and this article is not going to pretend otherwise. We are not in a position to tell anyone to change their medication based on one study. The research needs replication. The mechanism needs validation. The clinical translation, if it comes, will take years.</p>
  <p>The diagnostic implications, however, are immediate and uncomfortable in the most productive sense of that word. If ADHD is partly — even partly — a disorder of wakefulness regulation rather than purely a disorder of dopamine signaling, then the 40–50% of patients who don't respond adequately to stimulants are not a footnote to the success story of ADHD pharmacotherapy. They are the most important data point in the field. They are the patients for whom the current explanatory model is most visibly incomplete, and the wakefulness-regulation hypothesis offers the first mechanistically coherent account of why that incompleteness might be structural rather than incidental.</p>
  <p>The deeper question — the one that the 2026 finding forces into sharper relief — is whether ADHD is one condition or several. The diagnostic category has always been a coalition: inattentive, hyperactive-impulsive, combined, with enormous variability in severity, neural profile, treatment response, and developmental trajectory. The assumption has been that this heterogeneity reflects variation within a single underlying pathology. The wakefulness-regulation hypothesis raises the possibility that some portion of what we call ADHD is a distinct neurological failure mode — one that shares behavioral phenotype with dopamine-dysregulation ADHD but operates through a different mechanism, responds to different interventions, and has been misclassified not because clinicians were careless but because the behavioral presentation was identical and the neurophysiological tools to distinguish them weren't available.</p>
  <p>That is not "everything we thought we knew was wrong." The dopamine hypothesis is not being discarded. It is being complicated — which is what happens to good science when better instruments arrive. The person in the conference room, staring at the document, genuinely trying, deserves an explanation that is as precise as the experience is real. The 2026 study suggests that explanation is more interesting, and more mechanistically specific, than the one they've been given. Whether it's correct is a question for replication. Whether it matters is not in doubt.</p>
</section>

